<div id='communityQuestionsWithAnswers'>
<div class='communityQuestionAndAnswer'>
<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<a href="/questions/539877-why-the-title-white-nights-i-can-t-stop">Why the title white nights? I can&#39;t stop thinking about this wonderful book.</a>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_539877'><a id="like_count_community_question_539877" rel="nofollow" href="/rating/voters/539877?resource_type=CommunityQuestion"><span class="likesCount">22 likes</span></a>&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;<a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F1772910.White_Nights">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/539877-why-the-title-white-nights-i-can-t-stop">5 years ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/539877-why-the-title-white-nights-i-can-t-stop">See all 6 answers</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/5713369-jane"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1400948711i/5713369._UY100_CR25,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/5713369-jane">Jane</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">White nights in russian refers to the phenomenon around the the time of the summer solstice when the sun doesn&apos;t set completely and so at night it&apos;s n<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">White nights in russian refers to the phenomenon around the the time of the summer solstice when the sun doesn't set completely and so at night it's not completely dark, it's just dusk. I believe the farther north you go the more pronounced the phenomenon becomes, changing from polar day to the polar night (several months of constant sunlight and then several months of comlete darkness). Saint Petersburg, where the story takes place, is famous for it's white nights, and is commonly called the city of white nights. In Saint Petersburg they last roughly from the end of may to the middle of june. So that's what the title refers to.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
