<div id="review_3999839226" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3999839226" />
    <a title="Matthew Ted" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/57003346-matthew-ted"><img alt="Matthew Ted" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1578773686p2/57003346.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3999839226?book_show_action=true">May 13, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Matthew Ted" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Matthew Ted" href="/user/show/57003346-matthew-ted">Matthew Ted</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780241252086" href="/book/show/29610266-white-nights">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/57003346-matthew-ted?shelf=19th-century">19th-century</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/57003346-matthew-ted?shelf=foreign-translated">foreign-translated</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/57003346-matthew-ted?shelf=read-2021">read-2021</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/57003346-matthew-ted?shelf=lit-writ-russian">lit-writ-russian</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3999839226" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15982848734924892649">51st book of 2021.<br/><br/>I usually distrust these small books, which I refer to as &quot;till books&quot;, and not endearingly, but this was a pleasant surprise. On wanting to read Dostoyevsky&apos;s (Dostoevsky&apos;s) novella, <i>White Nights</i>, I found this small black Penguin &quot;till book&quot; also includes a short story, &quot;Bobok&quot;. They are packaged together as both being tales of unrequited love, though I&apos;m not sure how much that applies to the second story. The first story follows a man and a woman befriending one another and s</span>
  <span id="freeText15982848734924892649" style="display:none">51st book of 2021.<br /><br />I usually distrust these small books, which I refer to as "till books", and not endearingly, but this was a pleasant surprise. On wanting to read Dostoyevsky's (Dostoevsky's) novella, <i>White Nights</i>, I found this small black Penguin "till book" also includes a short story, "Bobok". They are packaged together as both being tales of unrequited love, though I'm not sure how much that applies to the second story. The first story follows a man and a woman befriending one another and sharing their stories. The male character goes on a rather long fairly typical Dostoevskian tirade about how lonely he is/how disillusioned from the world he feels/how he has no friends/how no one likes him/how no woman has ever loved him/etc; it was nothing I haven't read before, or felt that way. He's a less dangerous Raskolnikov, in a way, and therefore a less interesting one. It's not bad though by any measure and has quite a poignant ending.<br /><br />The second story, "Bobok", is a change in tone. A strange fellow finds himself in a graveyard and can hear the buried dead conversing with one another. It's a slightly humorous and strange story, not very long, and really a bonus to reading the aforementioned novella. I couldn't/can't complain. This year I'm hoping to finally get around to reading <i>The Brothers Karamazov</i> so I'm not finished with ol' Dostoyevsky in '21 yet.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15982848734924892649" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


