<div id="review_3714236039" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3714236039" />
    <a title="Kalliope" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3593962-kalliope"><img alt="Kalliope" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1428482885p2/3593962.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3714236039?book_show_action=true">Dec 27, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kalliope" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kalliope" href="/user/show/3593962-kalliope">Kalliope</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781482065978" href="/book/show/4518919-white-nights">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3593962-kalliope?shelf=19-century">19-century</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3593962-kalliope?shelf=russia">russia</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3593962-kalliope?shelf=2020">2020</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3593962-kalliope?shelf=translation">translation</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3714236039" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4317296377034033459"><img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1609173672i/30600599._SX540_.jpg' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/><br/><br/>I wonder if there has been a writer more successful at evoking the feeling of solitude than Dostoyevsky. I was surprised that he also centered his pen at evoking the other feeling that is a panacea for loneliness—love. Or maybe I ought not to have been surprised at the latter, given that it is a favorite story of a good friend of mine, someone who would appreciate the altruistic and dream like depiction of romance.<br/><br/>What also drew my attention, though, were other things. <br/><br/>One was the references to </span>
  <span id="freeText4317296377034033459" style="display:none"><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1609173672i/30600599._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><br>I wonder if there has been a writer more successful at evoking the feeling of solitude than Dostoyevsky. I was surprised that he also centered his pen at evoking the other feeling that is a panacea for loneliness—love. Or maybe I ought not to have been surprised at the latter, given that it is a favorite story of a good friend of mine, someone who would appreciate the altruistic and dream like depiction of romance.<br><br>What also drew my attention, though, were other things. <br><br>One was the references to particular sites of Petersburg, such a the Kretovsky, the Kamenny and the Aptekarsky islands, or the Fontanka and the Black river (or Chyornaya Rechka), or the Pargolovo district. <br><br>Another was the references to music, in particular to the operas the <i>Barbier of Seville</i> and <i>Robert le Diable</i>. The former reminded me that this Sunday I will watch Don Giovanni but more interestingly, it made me realize that when we say that, for example, Mozart is immortal, that he really is. His works survive through the ages and they belonged as much to Dostoyevsky’s world as to mine. And the latter will always have Proust associations for me; incidentally I finally watched this opera thanks indirectly to the way Covid has turned our world upside down. The NY Met offered it this summer as part of their generous broadcast programme. <br><br>And third, what captivated me in this novella is the way the Narrator first becomes a witness, then a Narrator (for which he doubles into a parallel third person), and finally a protagonist. <br><blockquote>
  <i>You want to know, Nastenka, what our hero, that is I—for the hero of the whole business was my humble self—did in his corner..</i>
</blockquote><br>And<br><blockquote>
  <i>You describe it all splendidly, but couldn't you perhaps describe it a little less splendidly? You talk as though you were reading it out of a book."</i>
</blockquote><br>The literary consciousness is always there, as are Dosto’s models: Walter Scott and, of course, Pushkin. I wonder if I will ever be able to read Dosto without seeing him as a teacher.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4317296377034033459" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


