    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1485487242" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1485487242" />
    <a title="Steve" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17433080-steve"><img alt="Steve" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1420185854p2/17433080.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1485487242?book_show_action=true">Dec 29, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Steve" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Steve" href="/user/show/17433080-steve">Steve</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17433080-steve?shelf=russian">russian</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1485487242" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5942292314539884137"><img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1451641929i/17571145._SX540_.jpg' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/> <i><br/>Sitting beside you and talking to you now, I feel terrified to think of the future, for in my future I can discern nothing but more loneliness, more of this stale and unprofitable life. And what is there left for me to dream of now that I&apos;ve been so happy beside you in real life and not in a dream? <br/> </i><br/> <br/>For a change, our author, Fyodor Dostoevsky (1821-1881), needs no introduction, so let&apos;s get straight to the remarkable early novella, <i>White Nights</i> (1848). A nameless, first person narrator - young</span>
  <span id="freeText5942292314539884137" style="display:none"><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1451641929i/17571145._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br> <i><br>Sitting beside you and talking to you now, I feel terrified to think of the future, for in my future I can discern nothing but more loneliness, more of this stale and unprofitable life. And what is there left for me to dream of now that I've been so happy beside you in real life and not in a dream? <br> </i><br> <br>For a change, our author, Fyodor Dostoevsky (1821-1881), needs no introduction, so let's get straight to the remarkable early novella, <i>White Nights</i> (1848). A nameless, first person narrator - young, hypersensitive, totally isolated in the midst of St. Petersburg, and living in his fantasies (clearly Dostoevsky's alter ego) - stumbles into circumstances that allow him to speak to a woman who is not a prostitute (apparently for the first time). This woman, who offers her diminutive to him - Nastenka - is fairly damaged herself; for two years - from the age of fifteen to the present - her blind grandmother has pinned their clothes together during waking hours to be certain that she was not misbehaving. So she is actually receptive to the painfully shy narrator's clumsy and tentative attempts at contact. She asks for his life story, and this releases the floodgates of at least eight years of reading and feverish dreaming in isolation. The verbal deluge that results renders the reader astonished and yet tears him/her along in its frothing wake, as it does Nastenka. The young fellow is more than a little mad - not exactly uncommon in a text by Fyodor - but many of us can recognize ourselves in him nonetheless. Since Nastenka is the first "noncommercial" woman who has given him the time of day, our narrator is fervently in love with her.<br> <br>And then Nastenka tells her sad story, which includes the revelation that the reason why they met at all was because the man she was in love with (her grandmother's boarder) had failed to keep a promise. The narrator reels, but I won't reveal what he does and spoil the story for you. Dostoevsky's prose makes it all worthwhile.<br> <br>A brief encounter between two damaged and fearfully innocent souls drawn oh-so-vividly before our eyes. The young Dostoevsky had chops already at the age of 26!</span>
  <a data-text-id="5942292314539884137" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


