    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3317521509" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3317521509" />
    <a title="Chavelli Sulikowska" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16127160-chavelli-sulikowska"><img alt="Chavelli Sulikowska" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1534643154p2/16127160.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3317521509?book_show_action=true">May 04, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chavelli Sulikowska" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chavelli Sulikowska" href="/user/show/16127160-chavelli-sulikowska">Chavelli Sulikowska</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781793180261" href="/book/show/43486510-white-nights">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16127160-chavelli-sulikowska?shelf=classics">classics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3317521509" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18038128728491172099">“I don’t know how to be silent when my heart is speaking.” The Ruskie classicists really do self indulge in the painful pleasure of unrequited love. I also read Turgenev’s First Love earlier this year and found a similar, poor, desperate young hero who falls victim to a woman’s indifference.<br/><br/>Reminiscent, reflective and romantic is how I would describe this apparently underappreciated novella…“I like revisiting, at certain times, spots where I was once happy; I like to shape the present in the ima</span>
  <span id="freeText18038128728491172099" style="display:none">“I don’t know how to be silent when my heart is speaking.” The Ruskie classicists really do self indulge in the painful pleasure of unrequited love. I also read Turgenev’s First Love earlier this year and found a similar, poor, desperate young hero who falls victim to a woman’s indifference.<br /><br />Reminiscent, reflective and romantic is how I would describe this apparently underappreciated novella…“I like revisiting, at certain times, spots where I was once happy; I like to shape the present in the image of the irretrievable past.”<br /><br />The unnamed narrator is a lonely dreamer, he is both hopeful but hopeless! As a reader, we feel sympathy for his sorrow, but also frustration at his naivety. He seems a glutton for punishment, just asking to be taken for a ride or beaten over the head again and again! There are equal moments of tenderness and anguish apparent in this novella – “you would never feel that my love was a burden to you; you would only feel every minute that at your side is a beating grateful heart…” <br /><br />I much preferred Turgenev’s novella. However, Dostoyevsky does write with supreme elegance and descriptive licence “either the sunbeams suddenly peeping out from the clouds for a moment were hidden again behing a veil of rain and everything had grown ugly again before my eyes, or perhaps the whole vista of my future flashed before me, so sad, so forbidding…” <br /><br />White Nights demonstrates Dostoyevskys’s exemplary writing, often characterised as existentialist, I found the story mundane and the characters a little flat – one dimensional you could say. I am sure there are superior examples of Dostoyevsky’s talent. However, despite not enjoying the story or the characters, I did relish his little pearls of insight and wisdom nestled throughout – “when we are unhappy, we feel the unhappiness of others more; feeling is not destroyed but concentrated…” if you are a perceptive and empathetic person, yes, how true this is…<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="18038128728491172099" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

