<div id="review_3184411349" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3184411349" />
    <a title="Ahmad Khalid" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/98472063-ahmad-khalid"><img alt="Ahmad Khalid" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1619203651p2/98472063.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3184411349?book_show_action=true">Dec 24, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ahmad Khalid" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ahmad Khalid" href="/user/show/98472063-ahmad-khalid">Ahmad Khalid</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781548269357" href="/book/show/39630904-white-nights">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/98472063-ahmad-khalid?shelf=standalone-novels-novellas">standalone-novels-novellas</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3184411349" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14394323037493825793">This is the first work I read by Dostoyevsky, and doubtlessly, won&apos;t be the last! I have been encouraged by many friends to give Russian Literature a try, and specifically read for this legendary author. That being said, I&apos;m really glad to have listened to them for it was worth it! Of course, I didn&apos;t want to get into chunky works for a start. So, I asked a friend of mine if 𝑊ℎ𝑖𝑡𝑒 𝑁𝑖𝑔ℎ𝑡𝑠 would be a good entrance to RL, and he highly recommended it.<br/><br/>This so beautifully written story follows a lone</span>
  <span id="freeText14394323037493825793" style="display:none">This is the first work I read by Dostoyevsky, and doubtlessly, won't be the last! I have been encouraged by many friends to give Russian Literature a try, and specifically read for this legendary author. That being said, I'm really glad to have listened to them for it was worth it! Of course, I didn't want to get into chunky works for a start. So, I asked a friend of mine if 𝑊ℎ𝑖𝑡𝑒 𝑁𝑖𝑔ℎ𝑡𝑠 would be a good entrance to RL, and he highly recommended it.<br><br>This so beautifully written story follows a lonely, young man who lives in Saint Petersburg. He prefers nights over days, and finds them more comfortable. Then, on one night, he encounters a sad, young woman, sobbing ceaselessly while distracted from her surroundings. He sympathizes with her and tries to comfort her, but fails on the first attempt. However, things happen and they end up getting acquainted on the very same night. They agree to meet againーso long as the man does not fall in love with herーand we get to know more about them through these meetings. I found both of their stories touching. I really loved their relationship at first. To find someone who you can talk freely with and who actually listens to each letter you utter is a bliss! Nonetheless, I knew things would change later on; they had to. <br><br>“𝒀𝒐𝒖𝒓 𝒉𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒊𝒔 𝒄𝒐𝒍𝒅, 𝒎𝒊𝒏𝒆 𝒃𝒖𝒓𝒏𝒔 𝒍𝒊𝒌𝒆 𝒇𝒊𝒓𝒆. 𝑯𝒐𝒘 𝒃𝒍𝒊𝒏𝒅 𝒚𝒐𝒖 𝒂𝒓𝒆, 𝑵𝒂𝒔𝒕𝒆𝒏𝒌𝒂!”<br><br>Suppressing your true feelings towards someone for the fact that they might simply not return them is a sad thing. Yet, it is much more sadder when you realize that even after you have finally gathered yourself and confessed to them, that person's heart actually belongs to someone else. The ending was heartbreaking in every sense of the word, yet realistic. After all, this is life.<br><br>𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐅𝐨𝐮𝐫𝐭𝐡 𝐍𝐢𝐠𝐡𝐭, 𝐛𝐲 𝐈𝐥𝐲𝐚 𝐆𝐥𝐚𝐳𝐮𝐧𝐨𝐯<br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1608855011i/30584074._SY540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>Favorite quote/line:<br>“𝑨𝒏𝒅 𝒔𝒐 𝑰 𝒂𝒔𝒌 𝒎𝒚𝒔𝒆𝒍𝒇: '𝑾𝒉𝒆𝒓𝒆 𝒂𝒓𝒆 𝒚𝒐𝒖𝒓 𝒅𝒓𝒆𝒂𝒎𝒔?' 𝑨𝒏𝒅 𝑰 𝒔𝒉𝒂𝒌𝒆 𝒎𝒚 𝒉𝒆𝒂𝒅 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒎𝒖𝒕𝒕𝒆𝒓: '𝑯𝒐𝒘 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝒚𝒆𝒂𝒓𝒔 𝒈𝒐 𝒃𝒚!' 𝑨𝒏𝒅 𝑰 𝒂𝒔𝒌 𝒎𝒚𝒔𝒆𝒍𝒇 𝒂𝒈𝒂𝒊𝒏: '𝑾𝒉𝒂𝒕 𝒉𝒂𝒗𝒆 𝒚𝒐𝒖 𝒅𝒐𝒏𝒆 𝒘𝒊𝒕𝒉 𝒕𝒉𝒐𝒔𝒆 𝒚𝒆𝒂𝒓𝒔? 𝑾𝒉𝒆𝒓𝒆 𝒉𝒂𝒗𝒆 𝒚𝒐𝒖 𝒃𝒖𝒓𝒊𝒆𝒅 𝒚𝒐𝒖𝒓 𝒃𝒆𝒔𝒕 𝒎𝒐𝒎𝒆𝒏𝒕𝒔? 𝑯𝒂𝒗𝒆 𝒚𝒐𝒖 𝒓𝒆𝒂𝒍𝒍𝒚 𝒍𝒊𝒗𝒆𝒅? 𝑳𝒐𝒐𝒌,' 𝑰 𝒔𝒂𝒚 𝒕𝒐 𝒎𝒚𝒔𝒆𝒍𝒇, '𝒉𝒐𝒘 𝒄𝒐𝒍𝒅 𝒊𝒕 𝒊𝒔 𝒃𝒆𝒄𝒐𝒎𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒂𝒍𝒍 𝒐𝒗𝒆𝒓 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝒘𝒐𝒓𝒍𝒅!' 𝑨𝒏𝒅 𝒎𝒐𝒓𝒆 𝒚𝒆𝒂𝒓𝒔 𝒘𝒊𝒍𝒍 𝒑𝒂𝒔𝒔 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒃𝒆𝒉𝒊𝒏𝒅 𝒕𝒉𝒆𝒎 𝒘𝒊𝒍𝒍 𝒄𝒓𝒆𝒆𝒑 𝒈𝒓𝒊𝒎 𝒊𝒔𝒐𝒍𝒂𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏. 𝑻𝒐𝒕𝒕𝒆𝒓𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒔𝒆𝒏𝒊𝒍𝒊𝒕𝒚 𝒘𝒊𝒍𝒍 𝒄𝒐𝒎𝒆 𝒉𝒐𝒃𝒃𝒍𝒊𝒏𝒈, 𝒍𝒆𝒂𝒏𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝒐𝒏 𝒂 𝒄𝒓𝒖𝒕𝒄𝒉, 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒃𝒆𝒉𝒊𝒏𝒅 𝒕𝒉𝒆𝒔𝒆 𝒘𝒊𝒍𝒍 𝒄𝒐𝒎𝒆 𝒖𝒏𝒓𝒆𝒍𝒊𝒆𝒗𝒆𝒅 𝒃𝒐𝒓𝒆𝒅𝒐𝒎 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒅𝒆𝒔𝒑𝒂𝒊𝒓. 𝑻𝒉𝒆 𝒘𝒐𝒓𝒍𝒅 𝒐𝒇 𝒇𝒂𝒏𝒄𝒊𝒆𝒔 𝒘𝒊𝒍𝒍 𝒇𝒂𝒅𝒆, 𝒅𝒓𝒆𝒂𝒎𝒔 𝒘𝒊𝒍𝒍 𝒘𝒊𝒍𝒕 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒅𝒊𝒆 𝒂𝒏𝒅 𝒇𝒂𝒍𝒍 𝒍𝒊𝒌𝒆 𝒂𝒖𝒕𝒖𝒎𝒏 𝒍𝒆𝒂𝒗𝒆𝒔 𝒇𝒓𝒐𝒎 𝒕𝒉𝒆 𝒕𝒓𝒆𝒆𝒔. . . .”</span>
  <a data-text-id="14394323037493825793" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


